In this project, I will Investigate and clean Aribnb dataset. This dataset for data cleaning originated from keggle challenge 3 years ago.  This dataset has six data file including across 190 countries. 

Airbnb booking challenger was predicting where a new user will book theirs first travel experience using Machine Learning algoritms. There are 12 outcomes of the destination country: 'US', 'FR', 'CA', 'GB', 'ES', 'IT', 'PT', 'NL','DE', 'AU', 'NDF', and other. 'NDF' is no destination found and it is different from 'other' because 'other' means there was a booking, but is to a country not included in the list, while 'NDF' means there wasn't a booking.

However,  My goal is learning how can I analyze messy dataset appropriately and what can I learn from it?
(https://www.kaggle.com/c/airbnb-recruiting-new-user-bookings)

Airbnb has to data to improve their service and marketing to recognize customer's voice. Airbnb did not know what kind of data will lead to their successes. They used a rich dataset comprised of guest and host interactions and build a model that estimated a conditional probability of booking in a location.

The main goal is to check the likelihood that a guest requesting accommodation would get a booking and increase the number of successful matches of guests and hosts to win for everyone.

Airbnb has to data to improve their service and marketing to recognize customer's voice. Airbnb did not know what kind of data will lead to their successes. They used a rich dataset comprised of guest and host interactions and build a model that estimated a conditional probability of booking in a location.

The main goal is to check the likelihood that a guest requesting accommodation would get a booking and increase the number of successful matches of guests and hosts to win for everyone.

Furthermore, They want to understand the quality of the trip of users. They measure user experience through a NPC(Net Promoter Score https://hbr.org/2003/12/the-one-number-you-need-to-grow) and A/B testing framework and ask users: "How likely are you to recommend Airbnb?"

Airbnb tested new ideas and improve businesses using data constantly.

* Summarize whole dataset


* Feature Exploration with main dataset: (data type: categorycal, Numerical, date etc)


* Calculate statistics


* EDA with Visualizations by features



* Outlier Detection

* Handling Missing values


* Transform String to Datetime 


* Converting Categorical to Numerical

source:
As you know that there are 6 datasets such as countries, seesions, User dataset(train, test for ML), age_gender, and sample submission. Sample submission is format that submitting predictions to kaggle competition. And train data has 213,451 rows x 16 columns. But test set has 62,096 rows x 15 columns with excepted column of the country destination(prediction for Machine Learning). 

At this time I will start with users dataset to investigate. Below is that I describe about 16 basice features.

* id :  (Object) user's ID


* date_account_created : (Object) The creation of account from 2010-01-01 to 2014-06-30


* timestamp_first_active : (Int) It is the first activity of users that they search before signing up.


* date_first_booking : (Object) Date of first booking.


* gender : (Object) ['-unknown-', 'MALE', 'FEMALE', 'OTHER']


* age : (Int) 'nan', from 1.0 to 2014


* signup_method : (Object) Facebook, Google, basic


* signup_flow : (Int)  The page a user came to signup up from. [ 0,  3,  2,  1, 24,  8,  6,  5, 10, 25, 12,  4, 16, 15, 20, 21, 23]

                            
* language : (Object) International language preference. There are 15 languages. ['en', 'fr', 'de', 'es', 'it', 'pt', 'zh', 'ko' ...] 


* affiliate_channel	: (Object) What kind of paid marketing. ['direct', 'seo', 'other', 'sem-non-brand', 'content', 'sem-brand', 'remarketing', 'api']


* affiliate_provider : (Object) Where are marketing is such as google, craiglist, facebook...


* first_affiliate_tracked : (Object) What is the first marketing the user interacted with before the signing up. 
                                        ['untracked', 'omg', nan, 'linked', 'tracked-other', 'product', 'marketing', 'local ops']
                                        
* signup_app : (Object) ['Web', 'Moweb', 'iOS', 'Android']



* first_device_type : (Object) ['Mac', 'Windows', 'iPhone', 'Other/Unknown', 'Desktop(Other)', 'Android Tablet', 'iPad', 'Android Phone','SmartPhone (Other)'


* first_browser : (Object) There are 52 kind browsers.


* country_destination : (Object) It is the target variable in ML. ['NDF', 'US', 'other', 'FR', 'CA', 'GB', 'ES', 'IT', 'PT', 'NL', 'DE', 'AU']

Numerical variable : 3 (timestamp_first_active, age, signup_flow)


Categorical variable : There are 13ea categorical variable.

### How do I address that lost data?

First, Checking the pattern of missing data. There are three types of missing data:

* Missing Completely at Random :  the propensity for a data point to be missing is not related to the missing data, but it is related to some of the observed data


* Missing at Random:  the propensity for a data point to be missing is not related to the missing data, but it is related to some of the observed data


* Missing Not at Random: First, Missing values depends on the hypothetical value. ( People with high salaries generally do not want to reveal their incomes in surveys).
Second, Missing values are dependent on some other variable’s value (Females generally don’t want to reveal their ages! Here the missing value in age variable is impacted by gender variable)

*  Dropping
* Impute
* Statistical value
* Linear Regression
* Hot-deck
* Flag

Listwise deletion removes all data for an observation that has one or more missing values. Particularly, Most cases, it is often disadvantageous to use listwise deletion. This is because the assumptions of 'Missing Completely at Random' are typically rare to support. As a result, listwise deletion methods produce biased parameters and estimates.

source: Removing variables if the data is missing for more than 60% observations but only if that variable is insignificant. However, Imputation is always a preferred choice over dropping variables.

It assumes that the missing data are Missing Completely at Random. If we delete pairwise then we will end up with different numbers of observations contributing to different parts of the model, which can make interpretation difficult.

Fill the values with mean, median or mode is a very basic imputation method. It is very fast, but has disadvantages. One disadvantage is that mean imputation reduces variance in the dataset. We can fill missing data with fillna().

# fill missing values with mean column values after convert data to numerical 

#users.fillna(users.mean(), inplace=True)

There are algorithms that can be made robust to missing data, such as k-Nearest Neighbors that can ignore a column from a distance measure when a value is missing and also algorithms that can use the missing value as a unique and different value when building the predictive model, such as classification and regression trees.

Sadly, the scikit-learn implementations of decision trees and k-Nearest Neighbors are not robust to missing values.

Another approach is One Hot-Encoding. It is to convert each category value into a new column and assigns a 1 or 0 (True/False) value to the column. This has the benefit of not weighting a value improperly but does have the downside of adding more columns to the data set.

Pandas supports this feature using 'get_dummies'. This function is named this way because it creates dummy/indicator variables (1 or 0).

'get_dummies'  convert this to three columns with a 1 or 0 corresponding to the correct value. This approach  is powerful because we can pass as many category columns and choose how to label the columns using 'prefix' . Proper naming will make the rest of the analysis just a little bit easier.

However, get_dummies returns the full dataframe so we will need to filter out the objects using 'select_dtypes'. It is very useful but it can cause the number of columns to expand greatly if we have very many unique values in a column. And, also we can use 'sklearn.preprocessing.OneHotEncoder()'.
